In the app, you leave it unbound or you use a provider method like that:
@Provides
UserDtoCrudServiceAsync getUserDtoCrudServiceAsync() {
  return UserDtoCrudServiceAsync.Util.getInstance();
}

public static final class Util 
   { 
       private static CompanyDtoCrudServiceAsync instance;

       public static final CompanyDtoCrudServiceAsync getInstance()
       {
           if ( instance == null )
           {
               instance = (CompanyDtoCrudServiceAsync) GWT.create( CompanyDtoCrudService.class );
               ServiceDefTarget target = (ServiceDefTarget) instance;
               target.setServiceEntryPoint( GWT.getModuleBaseURL() + "rpc/companyDtoCrudService" );
           }
           return instance;
       }

       private Util()
       {
           // Utility class should not be instanciated
       }
   }

So, instead of:
private UserDtoCrudServiceAsync userService = UserDtoCrudServiceAsync.Util
.getInstance();

You do:
private final UserDtoCrudServiceAsync userService;
@Inject
public MyPresenter(..., UserDtoCrudServiceAsync userService) {
  this.userService = userService;
}

CurrentUser is nothing more than a Singleton object, instantiated by GIN for you by the time it needs to be injected. It's a nice and clean way to keep and share user state among your client.
Try this in your GIN configuration:
bind(CurrentUser.class).in(Singleton.class);

